09538nam a22011775i 9783110736120DE-B159720221205051307.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221205t20222023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022943012  a9783110736120  a(DE-B1597)576420  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0110002bisacsh00aSecond Language Pronunciation :bDifferent Approaches to Teaching and Training /ced. by Ubiratã Kickhöfel Alves, Jeniffer Imaregna Alcantara de Albuquerque. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2022] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (XIII, 415 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on Language Acquisition [SOLA] ,x1861-4248 ;v6400tFrontmatter -- tAbout the Authors -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Pronunciation development and intelligibility: Implications for teaching and training studies -- tPlural formation in English: A Brazilian Portuguese case study -- tEffect of task, word length and frequency on speech perception in L2 English: Implications for L2 pronunciation teaching and training -- tL2 accented speech measured by Argentinian pre-service teachers -- tDynamic paths of intelligibility and comprehensibility: Implications for pronunciation teaching from a longitudinal study with Haitian learners of Brazilian Portuguese -- tPart II: L2 pronunciation teaching -- tA dynamic account of the development of English (L2) vowels by Brazilian learners through communicative teaching and through explicit instruction -- tAn extra layer of support: Developing an English-speaking consultation program -- tPutting participation first: The use of the ICF-model in the assessment and instruction of L2 pronunciation -- tPart III: L2 pronunciation training: Implications for the classroom -- tOrthographic interference in the acquisition of English /h/ by Francophones -- tImproving fossilized English pronunciation by simultaneously viewing a video footage of oneself on an ICT self-learning system -- tSpeech technologies and pronunciation training: What is the potential for efficient corrective feedback? -- tPart IV: Pronunciation in the laboratory: High variability phonetic training -- tOn the robustness of high variability phonetic training effects: A study on the perception of non-native Dutch contrasts by French-speaking learners -- tEffects of perceptual training in the perception and production of heterotonics by Brazilian learners of Spanish -- tAssessing the robustness of L2 perceptual training: A closer look at generalization and retention of learning -- tConclusion -- tAn overview of pronunciation teaching and training -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the field of second language (L2) acquisition, the number of studies focusing on L2 pronunciation instruction and perceptual/production training has increased as new classroom methodologies have been proposed and new goals for L2 pronunciation have been set. This book brings together different approaches to L2 pronunciation research in the classroom or in the language laboratory. 13 chapters, written by well-known researchers focusing on a variety of first and target languages, are divided into four parts: Pronunciation development and intelligibility: implications for teaching and training studies; L2 pronunciation teaching; L2 pronunciation training: implications for the classroom; and Pronunciation in the laboratory: High Variability Phonetic Training. Intended for researchers in the fields of second language acquisition, phonetics, phonology, psycholinguistics, speech therapies, speech technology, as well as second language teaching, this book not only summarizes the current research questions on L2 pronunciation teaching and training, but also predicts future scenarios for both researchers and practitioners in the field.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 4aAussprache. 4aSprachenlernen. 4aZweitspracherwerb. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Phonetics & Phonology.2bisacsh  aPronunciation.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  aSecond Language Pronunciation.  aSecond Language Teaching.1 aAlbuquerque, Jeniffer Imaregna Alcantara de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlcantara de Albuquerque, Jeniffer Imaregna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlves, Ubiratã Kickhöfel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlessenaar, Ilvi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCardoso, Walcir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCompton, Lily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotos, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Clercq, Bastien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDecourcelle, Quentin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegrave, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerwing, Tracey M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdalatishams, Idée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwijk, Lizet van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoto, Akiyo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarpava, Sviatlana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKickhöfel Alves, Ubiratã, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKkese, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKluge, Denise Crist